= Abstract
This work evaluates WebGPU as a compute platform for scientific simulation by implementing and benchmarking a complete Barnes–Hut gravitational N-body solver. The solver constructs and traverses a Linear Bounding Volume Hierarchy (LBVH) entirely on the GPU each timestep using the parallel method of Karras, combined with a symplectic leapfrog integrator, and is built from a single C++/WGSL codebase that targets both native desktop execution and browser deployment via WebAssembly. Performance is characterised across four WebGPU implementations (wgpu-native, Dawn, Chrome, and Safari) on an Apple M2, and compared against a native Metal Barnes–Hut baseline to isolate the cost of the WebGPU abstraction layer. At $N = 1000$ the WebGPU abstraction layer imposes a 2.4$times$ overhead relative to native Metal, but at $N gt.eq 5000$ the WebGPU solver outperforms the baseline, reaching 2.8$times$ faster at $N = 100000$; force evaluation accounts for 94–99% of total step time, with the LBVH construction pipeline remaining below 1 ms at all tested particle counts. Browser execution via Emscripten adds a fixed per-step overhead from event-loop scheduling that does not grow with $N$, preserving the sub-linear scaling observed in native execution and producing numerically consistent results across platforms. The 32-bit floating-point precision of current WebGPU implementations is identified as the primary constraint on numerical fidelity. These results demonstrate that WebGPU's compute shader model is sufficient for a hierarchical N-body solver with parallel tree construction, and that the abstraction overhead is modest enough for interactive galactic dynamics simulation without specialised hardware or vendor-locked APIs.
